Nokia is suing the Brno company for the name Lokia. People do not confuse us, the Moravians believe
Nokia has filed an opposition against Lokia's application to the Industrial Property Office. However, according to the CCV, product substitution is unlikely.
The Brno-based company developing CCV software is facing legal action from the Finnish telecommunications equipment manufacturer Nokia. Finns do not like the fact that the program of the Brno company for warehouse management is called Lokia WMS, wrote the daily E15. Nokia therefore objected to the Lokia brand's application to the Industrial Property Office. CCV considers that confusion is unlikely.
Marketing Director Petr Ondrášek stated that the program is already used by two dozen customers, it has been on the market since last September.
"The Nokia brand enjoys recognition and trust around the world. When someone tries to register a brand that we believe may lead to confusion or weakening of our brand, we take steps to protect our valuable asset," said Nokia spokesman Mark Durrant.
