Epilepsy has complicated his love of sports, thanks to the operation he has new hope
For the first time, Honzík's parents noticed that something was wrong with him, in a year and a half. He always stared into space for a few minutes, motionless and unresponsive to anyone. The pediatrician therefore sent him to the pediatric neurology clinic, where the doctors diagnosed him with epilepsy after a series of examinations and immediately gave him medication, which did not work immediately.
It took almost a year for doctors to find the ideal combination of drugs that completely stopped having seizures. At the age of five, doctors stopped his medication, and because the seizures did not return, his parents thought that Honza was healthy and began to lead him more into sports. He rode a bike, skied, played tennis and floorball, and spent his free time playing games with his sister and friends. At the age of eleven, however, he had another seizure and it all started again.
Doctors tried different combinations of drugs again, but this time nothing worked, seizures in the form of absences kept recurring. Since Honza always lost sight of it during the attack, his parents were terrified that he would get it during sports and get injured. Gradually, Honza stopped riding his bike and exchanged downhill skis for cross-country skiing and snowboarding. Although the sport caused him a seizure from time to time, he never gave it up completely. He even fulfilled his dream and finished the Spartan Race, but together with a friend who was always in sight to help him in case of emergency.
When Honza was 15 years old, his parents decided to try to change doctors and turned to experts at the University Hospital in Motol. After a series of examinations, local doctors decided that Honza was a candidate for surgery to remove a lesion from his brain - a source of epileptic seizures. "I had to have 2 surgeries in a row, first the doctors operated into my brain probes that sensed his activity, then they could remove my bearing. It was a hell of a few weeks for me. I just had to lie down and hardly move, wires stuck out of my head that were connected to a computer, "recalls Honza.
The operation was successful and the doctors removed a relatively large deposit. "The first days after the operation it was very mentally demanding, Honza was apathetic, confused, sad and almost did not speak. Unlike how normally he is alive and communicative, it was a scary change, but fortunately everything returned to normal after a few days," he describes. mother and adds: "A month and a half after the operation he had 1 seizure, but according to doctors it happens. Since then he has been without a seizure for 3 months."
This school year, Honza will graduate, in addition to sports, he enjoys languages and has started cooperating with Company E, with which he travels around schools to discuss epilepsy. Honza is not yet fully engaged in sports activities, he is starting to return to sports gradually. "I'm learning how to play sports properly, how to breathe well so that I don't expose my body to sudden stress, which is quite a problem with my competitive nature," explains Honza.
This year, therefore, they will not yet actively participate in the traditional EPPI boating triathlon, where patients with epilepsy and healthy athletes meet and which takes place this weekend on September 28, 2019 at Veselská pískovna. But maybe next year.
