Microplasts reached the human gut, the study confirmed for the first time
Scientists have been confirmed for several years. A team led by Professor Philipp Schwabl, a professor at the University of Vienna, published a study that for the first time proves the presence of microplastics in human stool. Although the study is small, with eight participants from Europe, Japan and Russia - however, in the samples of all subjects, small particles of plastic with dimensions between 50 and 500 micrometers were found. None of the eight subjects were vegetarians, six of them did not avoid sea fish, all drank water from plastic bottles and food packed in plastic.
And it would actually be a bit of a miracle if nothing was found. We already know that microplastics - which are either produced directly, for example for the cosmetics industry, or are formed by the disintegration of larger pieces - are present in marine animals, insects, tap water and lemonades; in short, everywhere on the planet. Thus, their entry into the human digestive tract has only been officially confirmed. There were about 20 microplast particles per ten grams of stool, and scientists estimate that more than half of the world's population will have them.
Lay and scientific awareness, of course, suspects that it is not good. However, humanity still does not know how bad it is - and what effect microplastics have on "host" organisms. Small particles can enter the bloodstream or lymphatic system and end up in the liver, for example. "This is the first study of its kind to confirm what we have thought for a long time. Now that we have the first evidence of microplastics in the human body, we must continue to investigate what exactly this means for human health," says Schwabl.
So far, it is known that microplastics in the intestines can negatively affect the immune reactions of the digestive system, and thus facilitate the absorption of toxic chemicals and other pathogens into the body. And so far no other known solution is to limit the use of plastics, especially polypropylene. However, this will be difficult - the first task facing governments and authorities will at least stop its sharp rise. As for plastic bottles alone, experts estimate that in three years, humanity will consume a fifth more than they do today. The current rate is captivating one million bottles bought per minute. About eight million tons of plastic end up in the seas and oceans every year. Waste threatens marine ecosystems and infects the digestive systems of marine animals.
Some states have already adopted restrictions and other measures, for example, Kenya has banned plastic bags under the threat of draconian penalties. The European Commission is considering minor bans (well-known straws), and the domestic Ministry of the Environment is heading in the same direction. However, critics claim that such measures are nice, but completely inadequate.
The repair of the Krkonoše Museum will be a year late
The administration of the Krkonoše National Park (KRNAP) postponed by three weeks the deadline for submitting bids to the second tender for the repair of the Krkonoše Museum in Vrchlabí. The original date for opening the envelopes was September 20, said national park spokesman Radek Drahný. The reason for postponing the deadline for submission of bids is the reduction of the budget from 110 million crowns to 83 million crowns.
"We are currently working with prices that are on the market. There has been a change in the budget, this is the price we expect to be offered. If someone submits an offer that will be acceptable, then the work will start as soon as possible," said Drahný .
Compared to the original plans, the start of repairs to the museum is about a year late. KRNAP wanted to have a selected supplier of the construction part by the end of last year and to start construction work this spring. According to the management of the national park administration, European subsidies of 123 million crowns for the project are not endangered.
The KRNAP administration is unable to select a construction company for the museum's repairs. The second competition was announced this summer, because in the previous tender all the companies' offers significantly exceeded the then estimated price of 65 million. The bids exceeded 100 million crowns.
The museum, which is housed in a former Augustinian monastery and belongs to the KRNAP Administration, has been closed since autumn 2017. The selected company should provide the construction part of the project. The total costs, including the construction of a new exhibition, are estimated at 210 million crowns. The KRNAP visitor center should be established in the now vacated building by the end of 2021 after the transformation of the expositions.
The renovated museum with a new interactive exhibition, which should be a story of nature and people settled in the mountains and build on the successful exhibition Stone and Life, should serve as a representative entrance gate for the Giant Mountains. The visitor center should provide information about the past and present of the Giant Mountains in the most understandable form possible and motivate people to discover the mountains and protect them. It should also take on the role of a traditional museum. The center will also offer opportunities for concerts, festivals, theater performances or open-air lectures. The plans are to build a new entrance to the building, create a research room or cafe.
On Saturday, Česká spořitelna incorrectly charged some card payments twice.
She has already fixed the error
On Saturday afternoon, Česká spořitelna incorrectly charged some card payments to its clients twice.
According to bank spokesman Lukáš Kropík, the problem could have affected thousands of transactions.
The savings bank has already eliminated the error and returned the money to the clients.
The savings bank noted problems with double billing of card payments on Saturday afternoon.
"Last night (Saturday) we updated the system and immediately returned all these duplicate payments to clients.
At the moment, everything works without problems, "said Kropík on Sunday afternoon.
The exact number of clients to whom the bank deducted money from card payments twice is not known to the bank's spokesman, according to his estimate it was lower than thousands of transactions.
The savings bank is investigating the causes of the problems.
"It could have been a combination of several factors," Kropík said.
Česká spořitelna is the largest bank in the Czech Republic in terms of the number of clients.
At the end of March, it had 4.6 million.
The savings bank is owned by the Austrian financial group Erste Group Bank, which is a key player in the banking market of Central and Eastern Europe.
