"A terrifying result of the study." Islam does not belong in the West, the vast majority of Austrians think
1200 respondents were interviewed, the survey shows considerable distrust of Islam in Austrian society.
Nearly 60 percent of Austria's population fear that some Muslims are terrorists, and 48 percent would call for a ban on mosques. 80 percent of respondents are in favor of more observation of Islamic centers.
Most Austrians also want Muslims to be restricted in their religious practices, arguing that because of the presence of Muslims, they sometimes feel foreign in their own country.
"The result of the study is frightening," says study author Wolfgang Aschauer, adding: "Such a tendency towards ethnocentrism could eventually lead to the adoption of discriminatory attitudes. There is a risk that the religious freedoms granted to Muslims will narrow."
For believers, the critical attitude is less pronounced. Aschauer argues that in Austria this is not a conflict between religions, but between cultures. According to the sociologist, dialogue and education could help blunt polarization.
According to the study, extreme right-wing voters, people without a university degree or seniors over the age of 75 have the most hostile attitudes towards Muslims. On the other hand, the most friendly are the Green voters, people under the age of 30 and university students.
According to estimates by the Austrian Ministry of the Interior, approximately 700,000 Muslims live in Austria, which has a population of around 8.7 million. The vast majority have Turkish roots. There are more than 400 Muslim prayer houses and mosques in the country, and Islam has been officially recognized as a religion since 1912.
Which cities will disappear under the sea?
A vote by the upper house of the Canadian parliament has confirmed a rumor for several days now: Canada is depriving honorary citizenship of the former human rights legend, Nobel Peace Prize winner Do Aung San Suu Kyi. The current leader of Myanmar (Burma), who spent years under house arrest in an effort to bring freedom to her country, lost her honorary title because of her part in the genocide against the Rohingya minority.
The decision to take Suu Kyi's honorary citizenship was approved a week ago by the lower legislature, and the senators have now unanimously supported it. "This is the right message for her, for Myanmar and for the whole world," commented the decision of her colleagues by Independent Senator Ratna Omidvar. "We must make it clear that the accomplices to the genocide are not welcome here in Canada - all the more so as honorary citizens."
Technically, the verdict of the Canadian parliament does not change anything for Suu Kyi, it is just an honorary title, but on a symbolic level it is a strong message for her. The silence of a long-time human rights activist against the atrocities perpetrated by the army of mostly Buddhist Myanmar on endless months for the Rohingya Muslim minority is unbearable.
The fact that there is an officially organized genocide in Myanmar and that Suu Kyi - the de facto prime minister of the local government - has completely failed in its duty to protect its citizens, a UN report recently said. In particular, it mentions the names of several army commanders who, according to the investigation team, should stand trial for crimes against humanity committed in actions which, as the report says, "shock both with the horror of their actions and the enormous scale". According to the United Nations, Suu Kyi and its leadership committed complicity mainly by covering up the actions of soldiers and releasing a fog of lies around them - for example, that it was an "anti-terrorist operation".
After the deletion of Suu Kyi, five personalities remain on the list of honorary citizens of Canada: Swedish diplomat Raoul Wallenberg, Nelson Mandela, Tenzin Gyamtso, the 14th Dalai Lama, Karim Aga Khan IV, the 49th Imam of Shiite Muslims and Malala Yousufzai.
Developments around the former icon of the struggle for freedom and democracy were also reflected in the Canadian Museum of Human Rights, where information about atrocities against the Rohings and the parliamentary decision to take her the title of honorary citizen were added to Suu Kyi's profile. "We have also dimmed the brightening of her photo on a human rights timeline board and are considering replacing her face with a portrait of a member of the Rohingya minority," Museum spokesman Rorie McLeod was quoted as saying by Canadian media.
The only thing that will remain so in the current upheavals of Suu Kyi - at least for now - is the Nobel Peace Prize, awarded to her at the suggestion of Václav Havel in 1991 for a huge contribution to the struggle for democracy. "While Ms. Suu Kyi's current actions are regrettable, her award will not be overturned," said Nobel Foundation chief Lars Heikensten of Canada's CBS.
