Francis Fukuyama's history is somewhat baked. In 1992, at the height of the wave of liberalism that followed the end of the Cold War and the fall of the Iron Curtain, this political scientist wrote in his most famous book, The End of History and the Last Man: the universal acceptance of Western liberal democracy as the final form of government. "
Twenty-six years later, we are witnessing more illiberal models from the United States to Russia, from Turkey to Poland, and from Hungary to Italy, and various forms of nationalism and radicalism thrive. Fukuyama's current ninth book, Identity: The Demand for Dignity and the Politics of Resentment, attempts to cope with the rise of these forces. As his interview with George Eaton shows for the New Statesman, he reconsiders many of his former views: he argues that the ideas of socialism should return to public space, and Marx was right in many ways. At the same time, he insists that his mental development is still in line with the position of the 1990s, and that critics have not understood the end of history and the last man correctly.
"What I said then was that one of the problems of modern democracy is that while it provides peace and prosperity, people want more than that ... Liberal democracy does not even try to define what the good life is. It leaves it they do not see the point in individuals who feel alienated and therefore group themselves into identity groups that give them a sense of belonging. "
At the time, the book The End of History and the Last Man was written as a strong argument against Marxists who saw communism as the final stage of history. When asked about how he now perceives the rise of socialists in Britain and the United States, Fukuyama replies: "It all depends on what you mean by socialism. If we are talking about ownership of the means of production, then except when clear services to the public are in demand, I don't think it will work, but if you mean redistribution programs that are trying to solve the huge income and wealth imbalances we're already witnessing, then yes, I don't just think he could come back, he should come back. the period started by President Reagan and Prime Minister Thatcher, in which certain types of ideas on the benefits of an unregulated market were discussed, had a catastrophic effect in many ways. "
In the end, Fukuyama is trying to calm the current situation and warns all liberals that even the advent of new, not entirely democratic regimes will not mean the end of history.
Civilization in the best time
Recently, I remembered a beautiful "message" from one of Šimek's great stories with Grossmann, which takes place partly in the cemetery, which reads as follows: "I warned her that she was crying well, but on a foreign grave!" It occurred to me that many of the world's politicians now engaged in a senseless fight against climate change are behaving very similarly now.
They act as if people are ruling the planet Earth. In fact, we are just a speck on her surface that she can blow away with her giant forces like a gust of wind, the flame of a candle. Probably few of them look at the famous British and American science documents dealing with the destructive abilities of our blue ball. After all, it would be enough for some of the larger active volcanoes to "slip" properly and our advanced civilization will regret it.
And it is highly likely that this will happen in the near future. According to leading volcanologists, many large volcanoes are "charged and unlocked" (for example, Katla in Iceland).
In a way, it would be ideal if the eruption, if it had to happen once, happened as soon as possible. Even before trillions of dollars are completely wasted on measures to reduce carbon dioxide production, because any really angry volcano, along with dust and poisonous volcanic gases, can release it into the atmosphere at least a hundred times more than has been saved at the expense of Europe's population.
Thus, there is no point in forcibly reducing CO2 production. In addition, it has been scientifically proven that with its significantly higher proportion in the air, plants form more biological matter and are also more resistant to drought. For humanity, possible warming is much more favorable than, for example, the rapid return of the ice age.
If we realize the hitherto insufficiently researched effect of solar cycles on the Earth's climate, we must come to only one reasonable conclusion: Let us strive to keep the Earth as clean as possible, and let us adapt to other changes with which we cannot compete with the least possible costs!
