The only ones. We are not sure of reproduction, but we do not have to scare
Some words have unfortunate connotations, even if they only state the state of affairs. They include the word only one. Indicates a child growing up without siblings, but does not sound neutral. "You know, the only one," they say, without the need to add anything. Interestingly, this feature has been worn by the "only child" for a long time, even from times when terms such as the demographic crisis were not widely used.
Today, even people outside the scientific community know that a fertility rate of 2.1 children per woman is necessary to ensure simple reproduction of the population. It is also widely known that no state in Europe today achieves this value. France and Sweden are the closest to it, but European countries do not have a simple level of population reproduction. (Within the West, only Israel stands out with a total fertility rate of 3.1 children per woman.) This is a situation made for alarmism. That's why it's no wonder that the Minister of Labor and Social Affairs, Maláčová, also fails: "There are almost as many single women as there are two-child families," she told LN in an interview. But she forgot the devil hidden in detail.
Yes, it is good to point out a problem instead of downplaying or ideologizing it. For example, as in Germany, where the campaign for more children easily gets the label of fascism (in the style of "Hitler also supported it"). It is good to remember that many couples plan their only ones directly. It is good for politicians to show a willingness to remove the obstacles that lead to those decisions (for example, a slight increase in work from home discourages women from further pregnancies). But in spite of all this, let us point out one thing.
If Minister Maláčová says that "there are almost so many only ones", there is a drop in demagoguery. That statement was appropriate twenty years ago. Let us recall that fertility in the Czech Republic last ensured simple reproduction in 1980 ("Husák's children"). Then it fell to a terrible 1.14 in 2000. But since then it has risen by almost fifty percent, to the current 1.70 children per woman, which is above the European average. This is not enough for simple reproduction, so the activity of politicians is appropriate. Only with that alarmism can they take a little.
