Declaration of the end of the right in the Chamber of Deputies or How the "right-wing" coalition of ODS, TOP 09, STAN and KDU?
There have been recent reports in the media and comments about the upcoming coalition of these parties. Many applaud that the "right" is finally coming together, but I rather wonder why these parties still call themselves right-wing.
Leaving aside the new Tricolor movement, the Czech Chamber of Deputies no longer has a real right-wing party. And it doesn't matter how the subjects label themselves or what the label streams to the mainstream media. The ODS is hardly central in its average of the top politicians of this party, TOP 09 is clearly a party of the city's pseudoliberal left (which is ashamed of its leftism, and so is hypocritically referred to as conservative or even right-wing). STAN is a party that basically coincides with TOP 09 in its conception, ideology and electoral targeting (the reason for its existence is simply not clear to me). And KDU has even labeled itself as a centerpiece for a long time - but their political compass is much more to the left than they say.
Do you feel like I've taken them all out of one water? No, I am based on the real political steps of these parties. If I consider myself a classically liberal right-wing voter, the highest value for me is the freedom of the individual, the free market and minimal state intervention in the lives of individuals and the economy. How do these parties fulfill this general presumption of rightness? How many laws slashing people's freedoms by the salami method, raising taxes, confirming new regulations and growing surveillance, increasing the link to the socialist EU or promoting environmental and gender madness have supported it in recent years? A lot, a lot. Not custom stickers, but actions identify them. These parties, despite all sorts of declarations or partial concessions, want to strengthen the role of the state in our lives. And that has nothing to do with right-wingness.
I would not be surprised at all by the coalition cooperation between TOP 09, STAN and KDU; However, the ODS has long been portrayed as "the only right-wing" and, by merging with these three entities, it already reveals its true political position.
By the way, when I mentioned those stickers briefly. Have you noticed how often all these parties identically and cheaply label critics of dirigisme and socialism coming from the European Union as pro-Russian agents? Can't or just don't want to understand that there are many people who don't smell Eurosocialism and growing lack of freedom as strongly as the authoritarian regime in Russia? Do they not by any chance hide their utterly arguable incompetence and the unreasonable or blind adoration of Euro-EU conditions?
In short, it is possible that in the Czech Republic, non-central politics no longer have a chance of greater success. Maybe voters really want that kind of connection. Maybe they want a center-left policy under the guise of the "right," because they are ashamed (or can't even identify) of their political beliefs. I don't know. But I am definitely not one of those voters.
