Thank you for the dance! Singer Leonard Cohen will release his last album posthumously
The album Thanks for the Dance will feature unreleased material and various musical collaborations put together by the singer's son. The album will be released on November 22.
In October 2016, the album You Want it Darker was released, on which Cohen collaborated with his son Adam. He asked him to help him complete the individual songs. On an intimate recording, Cohen symbolically copes with the impending death. He died a month after the release of the album at the age of 82.
Seven months later, Adam Cohen began working on the materials he had left over from his father. He invited a number of musicians to collaborate - at random Damien Rice, Bryce Dessner, Javier Mas or singer Beck.
"When we came up with the music for my father's words, we used his own distinctive musical techniques. He's still with us," Adam Cohen told the album. "What impresses me most about the reactions of those who have heard him. One by one, they say that Leonard is still alive," he added.
The first swallow of the album is the short song The Goal. "I'm almost alive, I'm almost home," Cohen sings in his distinctive honey voice. He sang about death, suspecting that the release of new material would not survive. He also admitted this in an interview with The New Yorker magazine a month before his death. "I'm ready to die. I hope it won't be too uncomfortable," he said.
In September 2018, Adam Cohen published a collection of his father's poetry called The Flame. It will be published in Czech under the title Plamen on December 31 at the Argo publishing house.
On holiday only with a credit card? NEO account offers withdrawals from ATMs around the world for free!
According to surveys, about half of all Czechs who go abroad have become accustomed to paying directly with a card. The main reasons include comfort, security, but also the opportunity to use travel insurance, which is often associated with a payment card.
Travelers in almost every corner of the world can appreciate the convenience of paying by card. This is especially true in popular tourist destinations, but today credit cards are accepted almost everywhere. "People who travel more often, for example for work, do not have time to go to exchange offices repeatedly to exchange cash. And even 'holidaymakers' do not want to rely on cash being enough for them. In addition, some foreign currencies do not even have Czech banks or exchange offices. With the NEO account, we therefore solved this so that its users can withdraw cash from all ATMs free of charge, wherever they are, "says Kateřina Petko, Marketing and Communications Director and Spobank CZ Spokeswoman.
In addition, a payment card is a much more reliable way to avoid losing your money than cash. When losing a full wallet, its owner no longer has to wait for the money he carried in it. However, if he loses only his payment card, he can easily block it immediately over the phone or via internet banking. He does not have to suffer any financial loss at all when acting quickly. "In addition to reliable protection, keeping money in a bank account has other advantages. For example, the NEO account has an interest rate of 1.6% per year, which is one of the highest among current and savings accounts. It is set up and managed completely online without having to visit a branch. In addition, the money in the bank account is insured up to 100,000 euros and the account management is completely free, "adds Kateřina Petko.
Travel insurance should be a matter of course for anyone planning to go abroad. Thanks to the possibility of arranging it and paying with a card online, this can be done even at the last minute. However, the mere ownership of a payment card often means insurance protection when traveling. "For example, with embossed MasterCard Gold and MasterCard Business cards, travel insurance is an integral part of trips abroad to all countries around the world. Holders of these cards can also insure their family with whom they travel. CZ. However, it is always advisable to check the scope of the insurance, ie whether it applies to all activities that travelers plan to undertake.
The meal plan has been planned by the ministry since 2021. Nothing has changed in the tax
The Ministry of Finance is preparing an amendment to the Income Tax Act, according to which the employee would receive money for food directly. According to the Ministry of Finance, a quarter of employees, ie about one million people who do not yet receive meal vouchers, will thus receive meals.
According to the chairman of the Association of Voucher System Operators, David Rýc, however, even a number of small companies that do not have a canteen or meal vouchers provide meals to their employees, for example by importing food or by agreement with restaurants.
"The essence of the plan is that we do not change anything in the tax benefit. It will not pay for health and social insurance," Schiller said on Friday. She added that the limit for the maximum employer's contribution applicable as a tax credit would also be maintained.
The Income Tax Act allows companies to pay a maximum of 55 percent of the price of a meal voucher. The remaining part is paid by the employee, in some cases paid by the employer, but without a tax rebate. The best value of a meal voucher for employees and employers this year is CZK 123.
Bloomberg: Venezuela has hidden bitcoins and doesn't know what to do with them
Venezuela's central bank is conducting internal tests to see if it can hold cryptocurrencies. It thus responds to an instruction from the state-owned Petróleos de Venezuela (PDVSA), which seeks to send bitcoins and ethers to the central bank and then pay the cryptocurrency payments to the oil company's suppliers. Employees are also studying a proposal for the central bank to include cryptocurrencies in foreign exchange reserves, which are now close to the 30-year low. Referring to information from four sources, Bloomberg reported.
The sanctions imposed by the United States on the authoritarian regime of President Nicolas Madur largely cut Venezuela off from the global financial system. This has deepened the country's economic crisis. The current crisis is one of the most serious in the world, forcing officials to use a mix of different ways to move money. While Madur's efforts to launch the world's first cryptocurrency have failed, ongoing efforts to use digital currencies show how desperately the government is trying to find ways to circumvent the restrictions.
Neither the Venezuelan Central Bank nor PDVSA responded to the request for comments.
It is not clear how PDVSA came up with its own bitcoins and ethers, or how much value these currencies have. The company has problems obtaining payments from customers through conventional channels because large banks are not willing to trade with entities that are subject to sanctions. Last month, the company received most of the payment of $ 700 million (CZK 16.6 billion) in Chinese yuan because the parties could not find financial institutions that would allow the transaction.
PDVSA may not feel like selling cryptocurrencies on the open market, as this would require it to register on the stock exchange and undergo due diligence. Instead, he wants the cryptocurrency to be used by the central bank and paid with it to entities to which the PDVSA owes. Representatives of the oil company believe that the central bank is less exposed to possible obstacles that could arise in the payment of cryptocurrencies.
Bitcoins and ethers use a decentralized online ledger known as a blockchain to verify and record transactions. In some cases, relatively anonymous transfers are possible without the need for an intermediary. Few banks engage in digital currencies because of problems with money laundering and related client information that complicate compliance.
Cryptocurrencies after the debacle in 2018 are experiencing a return to prominence this year due to the expectation of their greater acceptance by institutions and Facebook's plan to come up with its own cryptocurrency. Even so, they remain unstable. Bitcoin has fallen by almost 20 percent in the last four days, but has made a profit of about 130 percent since the beginning of the year.
Commentary by Jan Šindelář: Managing railways as a company
The heavenly election, though apparently not entirely smooth, is the culmination of the sad story of the state's inability to give the railways a clear direction. The board of directors has been incomplete for over a year and it does not change even after Wednesday evening, because one of the members resigned. The provisional period lasts.
The selection procedure itself was a farce from the very beginning because the requirements for candidates were significantly reduced, especially in the field of practice. Compared to last year's selection, the requirements for the size of the company in which the candidate was to operate in the past have decreased. At first, the members of the selection committee and then the supervisory board played only the role of pimprlat.
Nebeský probably submitted the weakest professional CV of the five finalists, yet without experience from a large company, he rubbed experienced fighters from the management of logistics giants and transport companies. It was the participation of interesting managers from the private sector that was probably the brightest aspect (and the greatest hope) of the whole process. Today, they know that they only played the role of narrative backdrops in the political game.
Maybe Heavenly will surprise, show great talent and eventually prove to be the best railway boss of all time. At least in the beginning, however, it will be accompanied by the taste of political news. Czech Railways does not have an easy period, they have to cope with the competition in the liberalization of the market and the lack of employees in operation. Drivers, shunters and mechanics are missing. What motivation should they have for further work and respect for management when the state behaves in the top management like an elephant in porcelain?
The second important group are creditors. We will see how the tracks at the head of the tracks will interpret next spring when the tracks defend their rating. What is certain is that creditors perceive instability. It is sad that someone else goes to Moody's for České dráhy to defend the rating every year. The agency did not miss the frequent changes in railway management and political influence on the company, it criticized them this summer.
The YES movement coers, among other things, the motto that the state must be run as a company. For a start, it would be enough to run one large state-owned company as a firm, not as a state. Czech Railways is still one of the largest companies in the country and it would be good if the best led them. They reported, but the state despised them. It can certainly be argued that the post at the head of the railways has always been a political matter. But then we can forgive the pranksters with the tender.
An unusually open and unique painting by Karel Gott in Olga Špátová's feature documentary
This unique film from Olga Špátová's workshop will premiere in Czech cinemas next spring.
"In mid-September last year, Ivanka and Karel Gott called me and asked me if I would make a documentary about Karel's life with Karel again after ten years. I didn't hesitate for a minute! Thanks to my exceptional singing talent, artistic humility and immense diligence, it was and is a great honor for me. "director Olga Špátová describes her feelings.
Thanks to a quick agreement and agreement, the first day of filming took place on October 22 last year, and the last shots with Karel Gott were filmed a few days ago. The goal was and is absolutely clear - to authentically capture Karel Gott as a phenomenal singer who distributes himself to his supporters, as a painter, but at the same time a loving husband and father of his children. A man who for sixty years has been distributing joy with his songs to several generations not only in our country, but also in Europe, and in fact all over the world. A man who enrolled in the hearts and souls of his listeners by simply being.
The film is not intended to be a show of Karel Gott's undeniable fame and achievements. "That's why it's not even possible to compare my previous film The Gott Phenomenon with the current one. Everyone is different. At least by shooting them in a different stage of Karel Gott's life, and this is very evident in his personal, even intimate confession, which he gave us and which confirmed us all in what legend we have the opportunity to work and spend time that is truly indescribable, "adds Olga Špátová.
The creators captured Karel Gott during his performances, during meetings with his fans in our country and in Hamburg, but especially in his home environment, whether in Prague, in a cottage in Bohemian Switzerland, in a village where he spent his childhood, and in other places that played an important role in his life. Thanks to Karel Gott's sincere openness, the film will be completely authentic and unique.
"Olga has a great gift for filming with her close team, so that we are often carried away by the spontaneous atmosphere and naturally let it into our privacy, thanks to which I talked about relatively confidential topics. With my husband, cameraman Jan Malíř, We originally wanted to release the film in 2019, when I celebrated my life anniversary, but because I had another beautiful summer with my family, I wanted us to shoot as long as possible. , my wish was to be released in cinemas in the spring of next year. This documentary is a thank you to my supporters and all those who supported and accompanied me in my profession, "says Karel Gott himself about the film.
