Destroyed shops, fires in the streets, a memorial procession accompanied the riots
Five years ago, 43 students at Ayotzinapa University disappeared, and despite an extensive investigation, the case has not yet been clarified. The students were reportedly detained by police in the Mexican state of Guerrero. It is not clear exactly what happened next, but according to the investigation, the students apparently ended up in the hands of a local syndicate and were subsequently killed and burned, according to the APTN agency.
A memorial procession took place in the Mexican capital on Thursday, with families wanting to express their frustration that they were still unable to find answers and explain the disappearance of their children.
However, the mostly calm march was disrupted by smaller groups of vandals, who destroyed everything that stood in their way. Vandals destroyed shops and hotels, did not shield themselves or destroy monuments, set fires around the city and smashed windows.
Even before the march, President Andres Manuel López Obrador said that he would do anything to catch him and asked the public for any information that would lead to clarification of the case.
