Annex No. 6 / Project management methodology
1. Project charter
1.1 The purpose of the Project Charter is to define the formal management processes and manner of communication between the parties in order to fulfill the subject of the Contract so that the performance of the work or provision of services is in accordance with the Contract and this Project Management Methodology. The Project Charter makes available to the persons involved in the performance of the work or the provision of services those parts of the Agreement which are necessary for the fulfillment of its subject. The project charter determines the staffing of the organizational structure of the project, the method of communication, control and escalation mechanisms and the structure of the project portal, on which all documentation related to the execution of the work or the provision of services is archived. The project charter will be prepared by the project leader and approved by the introductory meeting of the Steering Committee.
2. Organizational structure of the project
2.1 The organizational units of the Project are (1) the Project Steering Committee (hereinafter referred to as the “SCP”) and (2) the Project Management Project (hereinafter referred to as the “PVP”) and (3) the work teams. SCP and PVP are permanent organizational units of the project. Work teams are temporary organizational units of the project.
3. Steering committee
3.1 Powers of the SCP / Steering committee of the project in particular:
3.1.1 approves the Project Charter; and further
3.1.2 addresses escalated issues that have not been resolved at PVP level; and further
3.1.3 addresses issues with an impact on the scope of the work performed or services provided; and further
3.1.4 addresses issues related to the delivery schedule; and further
3.1.5 addresses issues related to the remuneration or structure of remuneration for services provided or work performed; and further
3.1.6 accepts individual deliveries, services, parts of the work or the work as a whole; and further
3.2 SCP members / For the Client, the SCP members are (1) the business sponsor of the project and (2) the director of the ISIT division and (3) the project manager. On behalf of the Contractor, the members of the SCP are (1) a management representative and (2) a project manager.
3.3 The SCP / SCP meets at least once a quarter. The exact days on which the SCP meets regularly will be determined by the project leader in the Project Charter. The SCP always meets when evaluating a significant milestone in the delivery schedule (eg the start or end of the acceptance procedure). The SCP will meet whenever a project leader invites to the SCP meeting. SCP meets at the Client's registered office.
3.4 Agenda of the SCP meeting / Agenda of the SCP meeting and the documents to be discussed will be delivered to the SCP members by the project leader on behalf of the Contractor, at least 3 working days before the SCP meeting. At its meeting, the SCP will always discuss the project status report and draft minutes related to the acceptance of the delivery, services or work.
3.5 Right to invite experts and advisers / If a party deems it necessary, it has the right to invite experts or advisers to the SCP meeting, but inform the other party in advance and state the reasons why the presence of experts or advisers at the SCP meeting is expedient.
3.6 Voting / After discussing each agenda item, the members of the SCP vote on the proposal submitted for the relevant agenda item. Each member of the SCP has one vote.
3.7 SCP Decision with Impact on Contractual Conditions / If the SCP decision concerns the contractual conditions under which the work or services are performed, especially if the SCP decision has an impact on the remuneration for which the work or services are performed, the Client without undue delay upon receipt such a decision, prepare an addendum to the contract in question.
3.8 Minutes / The SCP prepares a minutes of the SCP meeting on behalf of the Client, which it delivers to the project manager on behalf of the Contractor.
4. Project management of the project
4.1 Powers of PVP / Project management of the project in particular:
4.1.1 controls all outputs of individual phases of performance of work or provision of services; and further
4.1.2 evaluate and refine the delivery schedule and the progress of work in carrying out the work or providing the services; and further
4.1.3 discusses changes that do not affect the wording of the Agreement; and further
4.1.4 manages the cooperation between the Client and the Contractor; and further
4.1.5 manage the risks and corrective actions related to the performance of the work or the provision of services; and further
4.1.6 escalates at SCP meetings.
4.2 Members of PVP / On behalf of the Client, the members of PVP are (1) the project manager and (2) the main business analyst and (3) the application architect. For the Contractor, the members of PVP are (1) the project manager and (2) the chief analyst and (3) the chief architect.
4.3 The SCP / PVP meeting meets once a week, at the Client's registered office or in the form of remote communication.
4.4 Agenda of the PVP meeting and documents / The agenda of the PVP meeting and the documents to be discussed will be delivered to the PVP members by the project manager on behalf of the Contractor, at least 1 working day before the PVP meeting. At its meeting, the PVP will always discuss:
4.4.1 fulfillment of open tasks from previous PVP; and
4.4.2 the course of performance of the work or provision of services; and
4.4.3 fulfillment and updating of the work schedule; and
4.4.4 problems identified and how to solve them; and
4.4.5 a roadmap; and
4.4.6 risks associated with the performance of the work or the provision of services; and
4.4.7 evaluation and other requirements for the cooperation of the Client; and
4.4.8 the condition and severity of unresolved defects or incidents; and
4.4.9 change requirements; and
4.5 Right to invite experts and advisers / If their presence is effective for the effective conduct of the negotiations, both parties have the right to invite experts and advisers or members of the project teams to the PVP meeting.
4.6 Minutes / Minutes of the PVP meeting shall be prepared by the Project Manager on behalf of the Client, which shall be delivered to the Project Manager on behalf of the Contractor.
5. Work teams
5.1 Work teams / Work teams consist of employees of the Client or the Contractor and, where applicable, employees of third parties. In particular, the work teams (1) carry out specific parts of the work or services provided and (2) provide the know-how needed to carry out the work or services and (3) provide factual and professional input for further decisions.
5.2 Roles in work teams / The assignment of roles is always adapted to the current stage of performance of the work or provision of services. On the Client's side, the members of the working team consist of:
5.2.1 Business analysts in the subject area / areas
5.2.2 Guarantor / key user of the subject area / areas
5.2.3 Technical and technological infrastructure specialist
On the part of the Contractor, the members of the working team consist of:
5.2.4 Principal Consultant / Analyst - Architect of the proposed solution
5.2.5 Consultant / Analyst
5.2.6 Technical Infrastructure Specialist
5.2.7 Developer
5.2.8 Tester, trainer
5.2.9 Operation and installation specialist
6. A complete overview of the assignment of individual project roles and their communication matrix is determined by the Project Charter. Rules of mutual communication
6.1 Communication management / Communication in the project is managed mainly by the project manager. Communication is always conducted objectively in order to solve individual tasks as quickly and efficiently as possible. Mutual, controlled, communication of project teams includes in particular:
6.1.1 Project meetings (SCP, PVP, consultations, workshops,…)
6.1.2 Acceptance and handover procedures
6.1.3 Transmission and storage of tasks, information and documents
6.1.4 Records of change requests
6.1.5 Records of defects and incidents
6.2 Project meetings - program and documents / The schedule and list of tasks from project meetings are always updated at the next meeting. The documents that will be the subject of the project meeting will be sent by the project leader to the participants of the meeting in advance according to the subject of the meeting. The documents are registered and updated on the project portal.
6.3 Minutes from project meetings / The project manager of the Client shall prepare a written record of each project meeting, which he shall deliver to the Contractor's project manager on the next working day after the project meeting.
6.4 Modifications and additions to the minutes of the project meeting / Modifications and additions to the minutes of the project meeting will be made by the participants within 2 working days from the date of delivery of the minutes. Negotiations on modifications and additions to the minutes are managed by the project manager. Modifications and additions to the minutes are not a place for discussion. After incorporating the modifications and additions, the Client's project manager closes the minutes of the project meeting and saves it on the project portal. The deadline for commenting on the minutes of the project meeting can be changed by the project manager by agreement. If any time limit for commenting on the minutes of the project meeting expires without the comments of the participants of the meeting, the minutes shall be deemed approved.
7. Risk management
7.1 Identification and registration of risks / During the performance of the work or provision of services, all parties involved identify and subsequently manage in a documented manner risks that may affect the quality of outputs or deadlines for the performance of the work or provision of services. Risks are recorded by the project manager on the project portal, including their severity.
7.2 Discussing risks at PVP meetings / Discussing and evaluating risks is a mandatory item on the agenda of every PVP meeting. The PVP meeting sets out measures to eliminate or minimize risks.
