Annex No. 7 / Incident classification
The items below are for inspirational purposes only. This appendix must be formulated precisely and exhaustively by the project manager.
Incidents from the operating environment
A Category A incident means an Incident in a production environment if, for example:
the user cannot log in to the Application
when the Application repeatedly crashes at the same step and the user cannot complete the critical process
when the system is too long (twice the defined performance parameters)
responses to user activity
when it is not possible to print the documentation or report for the client
when incorrect data is displayed to the end customer
Critical functionalities / processes of the application are:
opening or canceling an account
daily shutter release
A Category B incident means an Incident in a production environment if, for example:
the user's work is slowed down, but it does not have a serious effect on compliance with the work procedure
when non-critical functionality is unavailable to the end customer.
Category C incident means an incident in a production environment if, for example:
if it is a language defect or other than the agreed font
when there is a graphics error in the user interface that does not confuse the user in using the interface
if it is a defect Documentation
Incidents from the acceptance environment
An incident of category TA means an Incident in the acceptance environment if, for example:
it is not possible to establish a client in the system
TB category incident means an Incident in the acceptance environment if, for example:
It is not possible to change any parameter of the client account
TC category incident means Incident in the acceptance environment if, for example:
if it is a language defect or other than the agreed font
when there is a graphics error in the user interface that does not confuse the user in using the interface
if it is a defect Documentation
