The museum in Semily with the exhibition returns to the Velvet Revolution
Imitation of a standardization room with a television, in which footage from the brutal intervention of police officers against students on November 17, 1989 in Prague runs. This is also the new exhibition of the museum in Semily, which is dedicated to the Velvet Revolution. "The basis is to present what happened in Semily after the events on Národní třída," said the curator of the exhibition, Tomáš Chvátal.
"I would say that the atmosphere was basically the same everywhere, with the first demonstration in Semily on November 22, and then more people gradually packed up every day," he said. Among the most active were initially a group of local dissidents around Miroslav Matěcha, who was the only one from the city and the immediate vicinity to sign Charter 77, and the Dědečeks, who spread the Several Sentences petition. According to Chvátal, the Civic Forum was formed relatively quickly at that time. "One specificity is that there was a very strong group of local doctors in the Civic Forum," said the curator.
About 50 photographs should draw visitors into what was happening in the city at that time, the images were taken 30 years ago by Karel Bárta. A video from the general strike on November 27, 1989, shot by František Tomíček, has also been preserved, which will be released in a loop throughout the exhibition. Ivan Hlas also spoke and sang at the demonstration. The Semily Archive also lent a number of preserved banners of the time to the exhibition. "They said: Let's not get drunk with a croissant, From riverbed to riverbed, We don't want violence," Chvátal said. Some changes in the city were very rapid at the time, for example, already in December, in an all-mileage vote, the people decided that the square would be Riegrovo and abolished the previous name Gottwaldovo.
The exhibition also captures the events before the November events. "In the first part, we present to witnesses and students what was before such a late normalization. I think we managed to collect unique documents from Semily, whether they are banners with various communist slogans or a bronze plaque from the then museum of the workers' movement," said Chvátal . One room is supposed to evoke the feeling that could have looked like in the living room of an ordinary household at the time.
The last part of the exhibition focuses on what happened after the Velvet Revolution. It focuses on the first free elections. "We wallpapered one room with election posters. Those who have experienced it will remember the posters With us to Europe or there is Václav Klaus still under the heading OF with a beautiful motto Everyone for their community," added the curator.
