Babiš chose statistics such as good security (the Czech Republic is the seventh in the world), a low unemployment rate, and a low state debt for his optimistic view. Or a statement that, according to a recent study, our country is the twenty-fourth in terms of quality of life out of 140 countries evaluated.
However, developer Dušan Kunovský and architect Josef Pleskot presented other, far from "pink" data in a television interview on the occasion of the Summit of Architecture and Development. For example, that the Czech Republic ranks 154th in the world in terms of construction proceedings. It may be that the current economic "boom" will not leave any significant architectural heritage as it did in the past.
The biggest obstacle is not only the current legislation, but also the slow, inefficient bureaucracy. This is also documented by comparative studies in which the Czech Republic lags significantly behind the developed countries in the overall quality and performance of public administration.
Our country has simply not yet been able to make good use of the potential of the good economic situation of recent years to invest in the future. It is nice that salaries and pensions are rising, but people with a better standard of living will also want to have a place to live, to travel modernly and quickly, to have quality cultural stalls, to live without an unbearable environmental burden.
But in the capital city of Prague, for example, it has not been possible to complete the internal and external circuit for years or to build a high-speed railway or metro to the airport. And Prague does not even have a modern, architecturally daring national library, concert hall or national gallery. The reason is not only absurd struggles for architectural competitions, zoning plans and building permits, but also a kind of specifically Czech conservatism, which adheres to the motto "every bolder change is for the worse".
And when it seems that something more daring could be done, it will almost certainly be ruined by conservationists or other somewhat wretched associations, or politicians. In the absurd drama around Jan Kaplický's "blob" designed for the new building of the National Library, President Václav Klaus even wanted to attach himself to the excavators.
However, the list does not end with Prague. The Czech Republic is not able to complete its backbone motorway network, nor to start building high-speed train tracks, so Germany finally decided to run its tracks for super-fast trains from Berlin to Vienna by "detour" through Bavaria. In addition, repairs to the existing infrastructure are often drowned in Schlindrian. Getting from Prague to Brno quickly is a riddle now.
Babiš came into politics with the promise that he would "arrange things". But not much has happened so far when it comes to meaningful investment and speeding up cumbersome bureaucratic procedures. Although an amendment to the Act on Accelerating the Construction of Transport Infrastructure has been in force since 2018, we will have to wait for more extensive positive effects, such as easier expropriation of land. And the new building law, approved by the government, which is supposed to reduce the current average length of construction proceedings from 5.4 years to one year, will, if we are lucky, start to apply from 2021. But many people would probably not bet on it. .
