The launch of the new toll is not endangered, Kremlík reports. But the change of operator is at stake
On Friday, the Ministry of Transport began preparations for a new tender for the operation of a new toll system. It is a contingency plan that the state would use in the event that the current toll contract was legally canceled. In addition, the state is preparing another temporary solution if it does not manage to complete the tender on time. This was stated on Facebook by the Minister of Transport Vladimír Kremlík (for YES).
On Thursday, the Office for the Protection of Competition (ÚOHS) banned the fulfillment of the toll agreement between the state and the CzechToll / SkyToll consortium, with a one-year delay. The Ministry will file an appeal against this.
"The launch of the new toll collection system is not endangered. Starting today, we are starting the preparation of a new transparent tender procedure, the subject of which will be the services of operating the new toll system, which is now being completed by the CzechToll and SkyToll consortium," said the Minister.
In the tender, the state would look for the operator of the toll currently being prepared, which will be launched from December this year. It would therefore not be a competition for a completely new toll system, as was the case with the last tender, nor the use of the old system now operated by Kapsch.
However, according to Kremlík, the ministry is also preparing for the fact that it would not be able to prepare a new tender in time. "Based on previous experience with the course of the toll tender, I am deeply convinced that the Office is wrong and that it is not possible to objectively prepare and implement such a complex tender procedure and hand over the operation of the toll system to a new operator within the 12-month period.
Thus, in addition to the new tender procedure, the resort will also prepare a temporary solution that would resolve the collection of tolls for a transitional period until the state finds a full-fledged form of solution.
The state will probably not use the offer submitted to it in recent days by the current toll administrator Kapsch. The Austrian state company offered to operate the existing system in case the toll contract was canceled.
At the same time, the Kremlin reiterated that he believed that a backup plan would not be needed. The Ministry will therefore file an appeal against the decision of the Antimonopoly Office.
On Thursday, the Office issued a decision banning the performance of the toll contract. However, the ban will not take effect until one year after the Office's decision has become final. It is not final and an appeal can be lodged against it with the President of the Office. The Ministry and CzechToll are therefore continuing to prepare a new toll, which should be launched in December.
The CzechToll / SkyToll consortium won last year's tender for a new toll system and its operator. It succeeded in a toll tender with an offer of 10.75 billion crowns for ten years of operation. The current operator Kapsch protested against the course of the tender and the validity of the toll contract, which failed in the competition with an offer of over 13 billion crowns.
