Berlin will buy 6,000 former social housing from the private Luxembourg company ADO Properties SA for 920 million euros (CZK 23.8 billion), which the city sold 15 years ago. It thus responds to public pressure, which is rebelling against rocketing rising rental prices. According to Berlin Senator Katrin Lompscher on behalf of the Left (Die Linke), this is the largest such buyout in the history of the German capital. The opposition criticizes the move.
"The intention is to keep rents stable in Berlin and give tenants security," said Berlin Mayor Michael Müller (SPD) in a statement. "At the same time, we will continue to build new apartments and legally treat the rent freeze," he added. The municipal company Gewobag will take over thousands of flats located in the Spandau and Reinickendorf districts in the western part of the city in December this year.
