If the apartment expires during the rental period, the rental will end.
If the apartment is partially terminated during the rental period, the tenant is entitled to either a reasonable discount on the rent, or he can terminate the rental without notice.
Termination of the lease requires a written form and must occur to the other party.
The notice period runs from the first day of the calendar month following the termination of the other party.
In the event of termination by the landlord, the landlord is obliged to inform the tenant of his right to object to the termination and to propose a review of the validity of the termination by the court.
The Landlord may terminate the lease with a three-month notice period only for the reasons stated in the provisions of Section 2288 of the Civil Code, and is obliged to state the reason for termination in the notice.
The Lessee has the right to apply to the court to review whether the notice is justified, within two months from the date on which he received the notice.
The landlord has the right to terminate the lease without notice in accordance with § 2291 citizens.
of the Code and to require the tenant to hand over the apartment to him without undue delay, but no later than within one month from the end of the lease, if the tenant violates his obligation in a particularly serious manner, ie in particular:
a. if he has not paid the rent and service costs for at least three months,
b. if it damages the apartment or house in a serious or irreparable way,
c. if it otherwise causes serious damage or inconvenience to the landlord or to persons living in the house, or
d. if he unauthorisedly uses the apartment in a different way or for a different purpose than agreed.
If the landlord does not state in the notice what he sees as a particularly serious breach of the tenant's obligation, or if he does not invite the lessee to eliminate his defective behavior or eliminate the illegal situation within a reasonable time before delivery of the notice, the notice is disregarded.
The tenant is obliged to hand over the apartment to the landlord on the day when the lease ends.
The apartment is handed over if the landlord receives the keys and otherwise nothing prevents him from accessing and using the apartment.
If the tenant leaves the apartment in such a way that the lease can be considered as terminated without any doubt, the apartment should be deemed to have been handed over immediately.
The tenant is obliged to hand over the apartment in the condition in which he took it over, regardless of normal wear and tear during normal use and defects, which the landlord is obliged to eliminate.
The tenant is obliged to remove the changes made to the apartment, which he made with the consent of the landlord, if the parties have agreed that at the end of the lease, the tenant will restore the apartment to its original condition.
The Lessee is obliged to remove changes in the apartment that he has made without the Lessor's consent, unless the Lessor informs the Lessee that he does not request the removal of the changes; the tenant, however, cannot claim compensation, even if the value of the apartment increases with the changes.
The landlord may claim compensation in the amount of the reduction in the value of the apartment, which was caused by changes made by the tenant without the landlord's consent.
Equipment and objects fixed in the walls, floor and ceiling of the apartment, which cannot be removed without unreasonable reduction in value or without damage to the apartment or house, become the property of the owner of the apartment.
The Lessee has the right to request that the Lessor settle with him without undue delay; this does not apply to what the tenant has done without the landlord's consent.
The settlement is due no later than the date of termination of the lease.
The landlord has the right to compensation in the amount of the agreed rent, if the tenant does not hand over the apartment to the landlord on the day of the end of the lease, until the day when the tenant actually hands over the apartment to the landlord.
If a thing remains in the apartment that can be considered to belong to the tenant or a member of his household, the landlord will take care of the thing for the benefit of the tenant and on his behalf.
If the lessee does not take over the thing without undue delay, the lessor has the right to sell the thing on his behalf in a suitable manner after prior notice to the lessee after providing an additional reasonable period to take over.
This does not apply if the item is obviously abandoned by the tenant or a member of his household.
The Lessee may terminate the Lease if the circumstances on which the parties were likely to have entered into a lease agreement change to the extent that the Lessee cannot reasonably be required to continue the Lease.
In the event of the tenant's death, the contract is governed by the provisions of § 2279 et seq. of the Civil Code.
