Since Tuesday, the Czech Republic is in danger of heat, meteorologists warn of fires
Meteorologists' warnings about high temperatures apply to Tuesday afternoons for the whole of Bohemia, with the exception of the Karlovy Vary region, and also for southern and central Moravia.
"Exceptionally, temperatures can exceed 34 degrees Celsius, especially in Central Bohemia," they say.
People are advised to follow a hot drinking regimen and reduce physical activity at noon and in the afternoon.
Due to the warm weather with minimal precipitation, there will be a risk of fires from Tuesday morning.
Windy weather could contribute to their rapid spread.
Meteorologists' warnings about the risk of fires apply to Central Bohemia, including Prague, Liberec, Ústí nad Labem, Karlovy Vary and the Pilsen Region.
The fire warning will be valid until further notice.
"We do not expect significant precipitation that would mitigate the danger in the northwest and west of Bohemia at least until the end of the week," the CHMI states.
The Prague City Council responded to the warnings of meteorologists by banning the setting up of fires in risky places, which is to apply from Tuesday.
People in the capital will not be allowed to start open fires in parks, gardens or forests, for example, up to a distance of 50 meters from the edge of the forest.
Smoking and the use of pyrotechnics are also prohibited in these areas.
The measure will apply until further notice, said Vít Hofman, a spokesman for the Prague City Hall.
The French chef is suing Michelin for removing the star. I'm depressed, he says
Renowned French chef Marc Veyrat lost his third Michelin star in January this year, a year after winning it. He intends to try with the publisher of the Red Guide to obtain the exact reasons for the degradation. Veyrat also doubts the competencies of Michelin inspectors, who he said confused saffron with cheddar. The first trial is scheduled for November.
The chef of the famous restaurant La Maison de Bois in the Alpine region of Haute-Savoie lost one of the three Michelin stars in January this year. He will be sued with the publisher of the prestigious Le Guide Michelin because, according to him, the commissioners' conclusion was not duly substantiated. In addition, according to him, the asterisk was removed without any notice. "I've been depressed for six months. How dare you play with the health of the chefs?" Veyrat told the commissioners.
Michelin is said to have given the chef only vague reasons, such as the fact that the chef put cheddar in the souffle, which the inspection did not like. "I put saffron in it, and those gentlemen thought it was cheddar because it was yellow. I've been working with Savoy ingredients with love from the beginning," Veyrat said against the decision. He is convinced of the strong incompetence of the Michelin commissioners: "You are fraudsters who only provoke disputes for commercial reasons." Outraged, Veyrat does not understand "how could they afford to say that we put cheddar in our souffle". "They also offended our region, my employees were crazy about it. We have eggs from our hens, milk from our own cows, gardeners collect fresh herbs every morning," he said angrily.
The distinguished chef, always with a black hat on his head and dark glasses, is an opponent of the new generation of Michelin commissioners, and therefore demands the removal of his restaurant from the red guide. However, the publisher refuses. "If the company remains open and our inspectors re-select it, we will continue to recommend it," said Gwendal Poullennec, Michelin's international director.
According to Michelin, the chef's lawsuit shows that he has no meaningful accusations yet and that the lawyer will only help him to formulate it. "We regret that Mr. Veyrat is communicating rudely with us. But we will carefully examine his comments," he said.
In addition to La Maison de Bois, Marc Veyart owns two other three-star restaurants.
